Scooters are now being used in the fight against COVID-19. This is an Eastern Cape initiative aimed at taking emergency services to rural areas and over poor roads - on two wheels. The province has the third-highest number of coronavirus cases in the country. Courtesy #DStv403 EAST LONDON - Scooters are now being used in the fight against COVID-19. This is an Eastern Cape initiative aimed at taking emergency services to rural areas and over poor roads -- on two wheels. READ: Concerns mount over Eastern Cape COVID-19 infections The province has the third-highest number of coronavirus cases in the country. Health Minister Zweli Mkhize, together with the provincial health MEC, launched the EMS Scooter Programme in East London. Eastern Cape Health MEC Sindiswa Gomba says the province is trying its best to fight the virus. "Even if you are in the mountains Matatiele or Lusikisiki we will get to you," Gomba said. Mkhize said he's pleased with this scooter initiative, which has great potential. READ: COVID-19: Startling claims about Eastern Cape hospital "We believe that this is a pioneering effort that it should be adopted across the country where a lot of other parts of the country are facing the same challenge," the minister said. The 100 scooters have cost the province R10.1-million. EMS crews will be trained to use them at a time when the province has recorded more than 7,800 cases and 178 deaths. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.